
On April 1, 1960, the U.S. launched its first weather satellite into orbit. The satellite was named TIROS-1, which is short for Television Infrared Observation Satellite.TIROS-1 launched on a Thor-Able rocket from Cape Canaveral, Florida and entered a polar orbit, which enabled it to see the entire globe. It watched the Earth from space for 78 days before an electrical power failure cut its mission short.The world's first weather satellite, TIROS-1, undergoes vibration testing at the Astro-Electronic Products Division of RCA in Princeton, New Jersey. (Image credit: NASA)— Earth From Space: Classic NASA Photos (Gallery)— GOES-R/GOES-16: A Powerful Weather Satellite in Pictures— In Photos: The Advanced JPSS-1 Weather Satellite's Earth Mission The satellite was equipped with TV cameras and video recorders that transmitted images of Earth's cloud coverage directly to ground stations. This mission enabled the first accurate weather forecasts based on data and images from space. It also showed scientists that satellites could be useful tools for studying the Earth.Get the Space.com NewsletterBreaking space news, the latest updates on rocket launches, skywatching events and more!Contact me with news and offers from other Future brandsReceive email from us on behalf of our trusted partners or sponsorsBy submitting your information you agree to the Terms & Conditions and Privacy Policy and are aged 16 or over.On This Day in Space Archive!Still not enough space? Don't forget to check out our Space Image of the Day, and on the weekends our Best Space Photos and Top Space News Stories of the week.
